She flipped to a blank page, writing down the date. Then, below the date, she wrote: "5/11/648-12/13/648".
"Are you reminiscing about the past?" Avery looked at the old notebook and asked. Carly nodded. "Do you think they'll let you go out for Christmas? It's almost Christmas."
Carly knocked twice on the lantern, indicating "no". As Avery had expected. The Ice King never allowed Carly to leave, as he saw her as "flawed". Carly was born mute, and was the only girl in the family, with all the other children being boys.
Avery was also so, in her unique way. When Avery publicly appeared as non-binary, the world seemed to change as well. As punishment for being different from the rest, Avery was often assigned to work alone for most of the time.
Avery was also forced to serve as the princess's servant. However, Avery didn't mind, because Avery had a friend.
"Your birthday is coming up, isn't it?" Avery asked, remembering that the princess's birthday was just around the corner. Carly nodded, a faint sadness flickering in her shallow blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate?" Avery asked, recalling how Carly had responded to this question last time.
I don't want to. Carly tapped the table. Avery knew that was a difficult topic for Carly to bring up. On this very day, Carly was imprisoned in this room while her mother was executed. Avery had been an infant at the time, but remembered the anger of the servants and the citizens. Avery had heard that Elwynn Queen was a good queen and could even miraculously predict future events.
"So... what do you want to do?" Avery asked. Carly looked up at Avery with excitement. She handed Avery a piece of paper. However, as Avery looked down at it...
6-inch x 6-inch canvas
White, varying shades of blue pigment.
6-inch x 6-inch canvas, various colored paints.
Easel
"So... you want me to get you those things?"
"Great! See you later?" Avery said, standing up and walking through the scattered papers and notebooks.
Carly nodded, retreating further into the thick blankets, reminiscing about her memories.
Avery walked out of the room, feeling relieved that the princess was finally willing to try new things and making requests that were outside of her capabilities (such as paints).
Avery walked through the hallway again, trying not to pay attention to the whispers of the servants.
"I heard she was possessed by the Elwynn Queen, so she always goes to that room."
"I heard she was eating babies in that room."
"Is it normal for her to look like a man?"
Avery couldn't take it anymore, so she covered her ears. Avery went to the royal painter's room, which was located in the east wing, to the left of the second door.
Avery arrived in front of that door, which was just as ornate as Carly's, with a white dragon painted on it. The dragon was one of the six original dragons and was said to be the one that created the Ice Kingdom. It was no surprise that the painter, who liked history, had chosen to paint the dragon on the door.
Avery opened the door, expecting everything to be as it was before. There were paint tubes scattered everywhere, pencils and paper littered the floor, and easels covered every inch of the walls. However, the scene inside the room was a stark contrast to what Avery had anticipated. The room was spotless, with a red velvet backdrop and a stool in the center. King Consort Aquario was sitting on the stool, painting a portrait.
"Ah, good morning, Avery! Want to take a look at your future king's portrait?" Aquario asked, winking at Avery.
"Sorry, Prince," Avery replied, starting to search for the things Princess Carly wanted. "I'm just here to pick up some art supplies."
"Little darling, you're leaving so soon?" Aquario asked, "But I still want to see you!"
"I'm not celebrating." Avery found the art supplies on the list and put them in a box. "And I'm not a girl."
"Ah, sweetie, you know this is just a phase, don't worry, it'll all be over once you're grown up!"
"I have to go," Avery said, feeling uneasy all of a sudden because the Ice King was still going on and on. Avery recalled all the negative comments people had made about Avery's gender identity, and really wanted to get away from him.
"Are you leaving already?" The prince suddenly appeared at the doorway, ignoring the royal painter's call.
"That's not something a future king should be doing!" Avery said sternly.
"No one will believe you. If the painter is still wise enough to save his own life, he won't be spouting off like that either." The prince turned to glance at the painter before leaning in closer to Avery. "What do you think about a date?" Avery shuddered with fear. Of course, Avery had heard her fair share of threats before, but none of them came from the prince, let alone this future king.
"Do you even know what the word 'no' means?" Avery snapped, pushing the prince away.
"No." Aquario said with a smile. Of course, the prince who could have whatever he wanted didn't know the meaning of the word "no."
Avery rolled her eyes. "Why would you, of all people, want to go out with me? You have a hundred suitors, don't you?"
He smiled, interrupting, "To be precise, it's over five hundred." He tossed his head, shaking his hair in the cold wind.
"Look at that! Why me, of all people? I'm the troublemaker of the palace." Avery crossed her arms.
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen."
